-- 
ARM, Enel, Fiat, Vivendi, Volkswagen: European Equity Preview

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-05-13T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/arm-enel-fiat-vivendi-volkswagen-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 0.7 percent to 281.80. The
Stoxx 50 Index declined 0.6 percent to 2,637.31. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, slipped 0.9
percent to 2,917.05.  ARM Holdings Plc (ARM)  : Douglas Dunn will step down as
chairman of the U.K. designer of chips that help power Apple
Inc.’s iPhone no later than the annual shareholder meeting in
2012. Senior independent director Kathleen O’Donovan and a
nomination committee will lead the recruitment of his successor,
the company said. The shares fell 1.2 percent to 590.5 pence.  Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA (BMPS)  :  Italy ’s
third-biggest bank said profit in the third quarter fell 1.2
percent to 140.3 million euros, beating the 126 million-euro
average estimate of analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. Its shares
rose 0.4 percent to 92 euro cents.  Continental AG (CON)  : The tire and auto parts maker
plans to invest more than 1 billion euros in the tire business
in the coming years, particularly in emerging markets,
Handelsblatt said, citing comments from board member Nikolai
Setzer. Shares gained 0.4 percent to 67.46 euros.  Enel SpA (ENEL)  : Italy’s biggest power company said
first-quarter profit rose more than expected, as reduced taxes
and financing costs offset lower margins in Italy and  Spain .
Enel shares fell 1.4 percent to 4.68 euros.  Fiat SpA (F)  : Chief Executive Officer  Sergio Marchionne 
confirmed the Italian carmaker’s investment plan for Italy in a
meeting with Industry Minister Paolo Romani. The shares lost 2.4
percent to 7.16 euros.  Gamesa Corp. Tecnologica SA (GAM SM): Spain’s biggest wind-
turbine maker posted profit of 13 million euros ($18.5 million)
for the first quarter, above analysts’ estimates, helped by
foreign sales. The shares advanced 0.4 percent to 6.26 euros.  Icade (ICAD)  : The property developer controlled
indirectly by the French state said first-quarter revenue rose
16 percent to 354.6 million euros, aided by growth in its
commercial property investment division. The shares rose 1.3
percent to 88.29 euros.  Indra Sistemas SA (IDR)  : Spain’s largest computer
services company said first-quarter net income climbed to 49.7
million euros from 46.6 million euros a year earlier. The shares
fell 0.6 percent to 15.49 euros.  Lafarge SA (LG)  : The cement maker may consider selling
its gypsum unit, Chief Executive Officer Bruno Lafont said at a
shareholder meeting. The shares rose 2.1 percent to 46.65 euros.  Societe Television Francaise 1 (TFI)  : The owner of
 France ’s most-watched TV channel said first-quarter profit rose
48 percent to 48.2 million euros, beating analysts’ estimates.
The shares declined 1.8 percent to 12.50 euros.  ThyssenKrupp AG (TKA)  : The steelmaker wants to maintain
a role in its stainless steel business and may float it on the
stock market rather than sell it, Handelsblatt said, citing an
agreement between management and employee representatives. The
shares retreated 1.1 percent to 32.73 euros.  UniCredit SpA (UCG)  : Italy’s biggest bank said its
first-quarter profit rose 56 percent after it set aside less
money for bad loans and investment-banking income rebounded.
UniCredit shares fell 0.4 percent to 1.64 euros.  Vallourec SA (VK)  : The producer of steel pipes for the
oil and gas industry reported profit rose 35 percent in the
first three months of the year on increased sales, and the
company forecast higher earnings in the second quarter. The
shares slid 0.2 percent to 84.06 euros.  Vivendi SA (VIV)  : The owner of the world’s biggest music
and video-game companies said first-quarter profit rose 29
percent as sales grew in its video-game and Brazilian
telecommunications units, beating analysts’ estimates. The
shares fell 1.6 percent to 19.11 euros.  Volkswagen AG (VOW)  : The carmaker may invest in offshore
wind parks, Financial Times Deutschland reported, without saying
where it got the information. Volkswagen shares slipped 0.8
percent to 118 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
